# Remote JIT Exec Module Hardening
# Feature Request: Harden the remote JIT execution module for reliability and testability
# Date: 2026-03-24

feature:
  title: "Remote JIT Exec Module Hardening"
  status: proposed
  priority: high
  category: Infrastructure
  date: 2026-03-24
  author: "Bootstrap hardening initiative"

problem:
  summary: "The remote JIT exec module has fragile internals that allow silent failures and lack consistent testing interfaces"
  incident: """
    During bootstrap testing, 12 bugs were discovered in the remote JIT exec module:
    diff markers left in source files, missing class definitions, wrong imports
    (app.io instead of std.io_runtime), and zero-capacity memory maps. These bugs
    were invisible because (a) the compiler bridge used return-zero stubs instead of
    real compilation, (b) wait_halt used sleep-based polling instead of timeouts,
    (c) each adapter had its own incompatible API, and (d) there was no way to test
    without real hardware.
  """
  root_causes:
    - "Compiler bridge returns zero instead of performing real compilation"
    - "Sleep-based polling in wait_halt masks timing bugs and wastes time"
    - "No common adapter interface — each target adapter has ad-hoc API"
    - "No host-side simulation mode — all testing requires hardware or QEMU"

  bugs_found |id, category, description|
    BUG-01, source_corruption, "Diff markers (<<<<<<) left in .spl source files"
    BUG-02, source_corruption, "Leading space corruption in indentation"
    BUG-03, missing_definition, "Missing class definitions referenced by other modules"
    BUG-04, missing_definition, "Missing trait implementations for required interfaces"
    BUG-05, wrong_import, "app.io imported in library code (causes 120s timeout)"
    BUG-06, wrong_import, "Shell-specific imports in platform-independent code"
    BUG-07, memory, "Zero-capacity MemoryMap allocations (always a bug)"
    BUG-08, memory, "Memory map permissions not validated before use"
    BUG-09, compiler_bridge, "Compiler bridge returns 0 for all compilations (stub)"
    BUG-10, compiler_bridge, "No error propagation from compiler bridge failures"
    BUG-11, timing, "Sleep-based polling in wait_halt (unreliable, slow)"
    BUG-12, api_design, "Inconsistent adapter APIs across targets"

requirements:
  - id: "REQ-001"
    title: "Real compiler bridge replacing return-zero stubs"
    priority: critical
    description: """
      Replace the current return-zero stub compiler bridge with a real implementation
      that performs actual compilation, reports errors, and validates output artifacts.
      The bridge must invoke the Simple compiler pipeline (lexer, parser, type check,
      codegen) and return structured results including success/failure status, error
      diagnostics, and the path to the compiled artifact.
    """
    acceptance_criteria:
      - "Compiler bridge invokes real compilation pipeline for each workload"
      - "Compilation errors are captured and returned as structured diagnostics"
      - "Compiled artifacts are validated (file exists, non-zero size, correct format)"
      - "Bridge reports compilation time for performance tracking"
      - "No return-zero stubs remain in the compiler bridge"
      - "Bridge supports all target backends (native, C, LLVM, Cranelift)"
    current_state: "All compile() calls return 0 without performing any work"
    target_state: "All compile() calls perform real compilation and return Result<Artifact, CompileError>"

  - id: "REQ-002"
    title: "Timeout-based wait_halt replacing sleep-based polling"
    priority: high
    description: """
      Replace all sleep-based polling loops in wait_halt and similar synchronization
      points with proper timeout-based waiting. The current approach uses fixed sleep
      durations (e.g., sleep(100ms) in a loop), which is both unreliable (may miss
      fast completions) and slow (wastes time on the common case). The new approach
      uses a monotonic clock with a configurable deadline.
    """
    acceptance_criteria:
      - "wait_halt accepts a timeout parameter (default: 5 seconds)"
      - "Polling interval starts at 1ms and backs off exponentially (max 100ms)"
      - "Returns immediately when halt condition is detected"
      - "Returns TimeoutError if deadline is exceeded"
      - "No fixed sleep() calls remain in synchronization code"
      - "Total wait time is logged for performance analysis"
    current_pattern: """
      fn wait_halt():
          var i = 0
          while i < 100:
              sleep(100)  # Fixed 100ms sleep, up to 10 seconds total
              if check_halted():
                  return
              i = i + 1
          # Silent failure if not halted after 10 seconds
    """
    target_pattern: """
      fn wait_halt(timeout_ms: Int = 5000) -> Result<HaltStatus, TimeoutError>:
          val deadline = monotonic_clock() + timeout_ms
          var interval = 1
          while monotonic_clock() < deadline:
              if check_halted():
                  return Ok(HaltStatus(elapsed: monotonic_clock() - start))
              sleep(interval)
              interval = min(interval * 2, 100)
          return Err(TimeoutError(timeout: timeout_ms))
    """

  - id: "REQ-003"
    title: "Adapter interface trait for consistent API across all adapters"
    priority: high
    description: """
      Define a common ExecAdapter trait that all target adapters must implement.
      Currently each adapter (QEMU, JTAG, host-sim, etc.) has its own ad-hoc API
      with different method names, parameter conventions, and error handling. A
      unified trait ensures consistent behavior and enables generic test harnesses.
    """
    acceptance_criteria:
      - "ExecAdapter trait defines: connect, load, run, halt, read_memory, write_memory, disconnect"
      - "All existing adapters implement ExecAdapter"
      - "Generic test harness can run against any adapter via trait dispatch"
      - "Adapter-specific extensions are exposed through optional sub-traits"
      - "Error types are unified across all adapters (ExecError enum)"
      - "Adapter capabilities are queryable (supports_breakpoints, supports_single_step, etc.)"
    trait_definition: """
      trait ExecAdapter:
          fn connect(config: AdapterConfig) -> Result<Self, ExecError>
          fn load(binary: BinaryArtifact) -> Result<LoadResult, ExecError>
          fn run() -> Result<RunHandle, ExecError>
          fn halt() -> Result<HaltStatus, ExecError>
          fn wait_halt(timeout_ms: Int) -> Result<HaltStatus, TimeoutError>
          fn read_memory(addr: UInt64, size: Int) -> Result<Bytes, ExecError>
          fn write_memory(addr: UInt64, data: Bytes) -> Result<Int, ExecError>
          fn disconnect() -> Result<Nil, ExecError>
          fn capabilities() -> AdapterCapabilities
    """
    adapters_to_implement:
      - name: "QemuAdapter"
        target: "QEMU system emulation"
        status: "existing, needs trait conformance"
      - name: "JtagAdapter"
        target: "JTAG/SWD hardware probes"
        status: "existing, needs trait conformance"
      - name: "HostSimAdapter"
        target: "Host-side simulation (new)"
        status: "to be implemented (REQ-004)"
      - name: "T32Adapter"
        target: "TRACE32 debugger"
        status: "existing, needs trait conformance"

  - id: "REQ-004"
    title: "Host-side simulation mode for testing without hardware"
    priority: high
    description: """
      Implement a HostSimAdapter that simulates the exec module behavior entirely
      on the host machine, without requiring any hardware, QEMU, or special
      permissions. This adapter uses the host CPU to execute compiled workloads
      and simulates memory-mapped I/O through software emulation. It enables
      full test coverage of the exec module logic in CI environments.
    """
    acceptance_criteria:
      - "HostSimAdapter implements the full ExecAdapter trait"
      - "Workloads compiled for host target run natively"
      - "Memory map operations use host virtual memory (mmap/VirtualAlloc)"
      - "Simulated halt/resume via signal handling (SIGSTOP/SIGCONT or equivalent)"
      - "Register read/write through ptrace or equivalent host mechanism"
      - "All exec module tests pass with HostSimAdapter in CI"
      - "No hardware, QEMU, or elevated permissions required"
      - "Performance: test suite completes in under 30 seconds"
    simulation_scope:
      supported:
        - "Memory allocation and read/write"
        - "Binary loading and execution"
        - "Halt and resume"
        - "Exit code capture"
        - "stdout/stderr capture"
      not_supported:
        - "Hardware-specific peripherals (use mock)"
        - "Real-time timing guarantees"
        - "Multi-core execution (single-threaded simulation)"

implementation_notes:
  approach: """
    Implement as a library module (src/lib/nogc_sync_mut/exec/adapter/) with one
    file per adapter. The ExecAdapter trait goes in the adapter base module. The
    HostSimAdapter is the first adapter implemented against the trait, followed
    by refactoring existing adapters to conform.
  """
  key_files:
    - "src/lib/nogc_sync_mut/exec/adapter/mod.spl — ExecAdapter trait definition"
    - "src/lib/nogc_sync_mut/exec/adapter/host_sim.spl — HostSimAdapter"
    - "src/lib/nogc_sync_mut/exec/adapter/qemu.spl — QemuAdapter (refactored)"
    - "src/lib/nogc_sync_mut/exec/adapter/jtag.spl — JtagAdapter (refactored)"
    - "src/lib/nogc_sync_mut/exec/compiler_bridge.spl — real compiler bridge"
    - "test/feature/exec/adapter_conformance_spec.spl — trait conformance tests"
    - "test/feature/exec/host_sim_spec.spl — host simulation tests"
  migration_strategy: """
    Phase 1: Define ExecAdapter trait and implement HostSimAdapter (new code only).
    Phase 2: Refactor QemuAdapter to implement ExecAdapter (preserve behavior).
    Phase 3: Refactor remaining adapters (JTAG, T32) to implement ExecAdapter.
    Phase 4: Replace compiler bridge stubs with real implementation.
    Phase 5: Convert wait_halt to timeout-based across all adapters.
    Each phase is independently testable and deployable.
  """
  estimated_effort: "1 week for Phase 1-2, 1 week for Phase 3-5"

related_documents:
  - "doc/feature/bootstrap_test_gate.sdn — pipeline gates that consume these improvements"
  - "src/lib/nogc_async_mut_noalloc/execution/ — current exec module location"
  - "test/feature/baremetal/ — existing baremetal tests"
  - ".claude/skills/t32.md — TRACE32 adapter reference"
